  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uargfeld.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Argfeld</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 465<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/14/02 6:16:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1607.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Chick with kids</span><hr size=1> I am a guy by the way.  The following might make it look like I am a woman, but I am a guy.  I want to make this perfectly clear because, frankly, Anarkhan scares me! hehehe.  Also, I do not have a daughter of any age!<br>
<br>
If you look at things from the woman's point of view, she's got a kid or kids that she would probably like to see with a decent father.  There's a good chance that the natural father (assuming he is alive) isn't what she would consider a good father for whatever reason, even if the only reason is that she simply doesn't like him.  Who does she love most in all the world?  It's almost certainly her kids.  So, it is reasonable for her to be looking for a good father-type first.  Then, if she thinks you make the cut in that area, she might start checking you out for boyfriend/husband potential.  So, if she seems to be putting an unusual amount of emphasis on her children, that is probably why.<br>
<br>
Also, talking about the children is often a good way to separate the casual daters from the ones that have &quot;honorable intentions&quot;.<br>
<br>
Of course, this is a real turn off to men, not because they don't like kids, but because being a father typically means MARRIAGE!  And while most men (honestly) would like to be married one day, having a woman dropping what appear to be strong hints about marriage right at the very beginning when you barely know each other doesn't go over well!<br>
<br>
A woman with kids who is practical is not going to try and hide them from you.  They are an extremely important part of her life.  If you have a problem with hearing her talk about them, if it &quot;spoils the mood&quot;, then you should probably go find you another woman.  Likewise, if you can't love her children (in a clean, wholesome, non-Anarkhanish sort of way), then find another woman, no matter how appealing she might be to you.<br>
<br>
Keep in mind that if you end up with a woman with one or more children, that you will end up with a connection to the father of those children and to his family, whether you like it or not.  So find out a little bit about him before you date his ex, things like whether or not he is a member of the Manson family who gets out of prison in less than a year.<br>
<br>
If any of her kids have problems, you will have to deal with that.  If one of them is addicted to crack or likes to torture small animals, that will become YOUR problem if you marry her.  And even though she may like to talk about them as &quot;our kids&quot;, meaning yours and hers, just wait until you do something with them that she doesn't like, like spanking one of her children if she is against that sort of thing.  Then suddenly, it's, &quot;Get your hands off of MY child!&quot;  Notice how the &quot;our&quot; becomes &quot;my&quot;.<br>
<br>
Also keep in mind with any divorced woman that there may be a darn good reason she couldn't stay married.  Or perhaps I should say &quot;a darn bad reason&quot;!  A typical divorced person will not say stuff like, &quot;It was my fault!  I am so unforgiving!  I drove my ex away!&quot;  No matter how much it might have been the fault of the person you are talking to, they almost invariably blame it 100% on their ex.  I know a woman that is on her fifth marriage.  I would like to think that she has just had bad luck, but I have to figure that there is SOMETHING wrong with her, even if it is just appallingly bad taste in men.<br>
<br>
Many men, including myself, would like to have their own kids one day.  If I marry a woman with five kids, I couldn't afford to have my own (biologically speaking).  That is not to say that I couldn't love her kids as my own, but I would still like to have my own if I can.  Some women with children are desperate for financial assistance and it often shows.  Sometimes these women want to find and marry any man that would make a half-way decent father and help her support her children.  I sympathize with them, but I don't want to get a woman who is marrying me for my wallet, even if she is doing it for the sake of her children and not out of greed.<br>
<br>
Yes, I think that divorce has gotten way out of hand these days.  You are supposed to figure out if you are ready to spend your life with someone during the dating phase of the relationship.  Marriage is not merely advanced dating!  Too many people rush into marriage, convinced that love will conquer all.  It won't!  If you marry someone that is vicious, or unforgiving, or unfaithful, or lazy, or whatever, then you will NOT change them!  In fact, odds are good that the very best behavior you ever see from that person will be while you are dating.  It tends to go downhill from there at least a little bit.  If you date someone long enough, it becomes more and more difficult for them to conceal stuff from you.  If they like to cheat on their significant other for example, they might fool your for a month or two, but eventually there's a good chance you'll figure it out.  I highly recommend long engagements for this reason.  I also recommend that you marry someone who is religiously and politically compatible with you.  Is there anything you believe in strongly enough to get mad over?  Why not find someone who shares your beliefs in that area?  If your religious beliefs are important to you, marry someone from your own religious group.  I know it sounds funny hearing stories from comedians who come from a family where one parent was Bhuddist and the other was Jewish or Catholic and Mormon or Muslim and Baptist, etc., etc., but if either partner in such a marriage takes their beliefs seriously, it tends to cause a lot of grief somewhere down the line.<br>
<br>
And then, after getting married, too many people give up too easy or leave for the wrong reasons.  Now, I am not saying that a woman should stay in a marriage where her husband is beating her or heaping emotional abuse on her or cheating on her or molesting their children.  But if all he does is leave the toilet seat up and throw his dirty socks on the floor, she needs to learn to live with it.  Likewise, if your wife doesn't do everything just the way you think she should, learn to live with it!  I know this sounds odd, but marriage isn't about being happy!  Don't get me wrong.  If there is no happiness in your marriage, then something is horribly wrong, but there is no such thing as a marriage where everyone is happy all the time.  A marriage that doesn't go through some hard times is a rare sort of marriage.  When I say a marriage isn't about being happy, I say that because so many people get married to someone because that person makes them happy and then when they go through a non-happy period, they think it's all over and leave.  BAH!!!  What a bunch of wusses!  <br>
<br>
I don't condemn one parent families.  Many people from such families turn out just fine.  But a lot of them don't.  It's good for children to have a father AND a mother.  Boys tend to model themselves after their fathers and marry women that are like their mothers.  Girls tend to model themselves after their mothers and marry men like their fathers.  Take away one of these examples and it is possible to end up with some kids that have problems, that have difficulty forming relationships or keeping them.  Not to mention the logistics of taking care of children for a single parent can be a nightmare, especially if money is tight.  <br>
<br>
I am a fundamentalist, although I have to say that Fadingcolours and I would probably disagree on a number of things.  Yes, I wish that everybody did things the &quot;old-fashioned&quot; way, but I don't really expect them to do so nor do I hate them when they don't.  I wish people didn't smoke crack or drive drunk, but they do.  I can't change that.  I don't hate them for doing it, but I wish they wouldn't.  It saddens me more than it does anything else, like seeing a friend or relative destroy his life with drugs.  That's basically my attitude towards people with a more &quot;liberal&quot; morality so to speak.  Marriage is important.  Sexual fidelity is important.  People who value these things are not messed up or dysfunctional or full of neuroses.  They are often happy, well-adjusted people who gain a great deal of joy and satisfaction out of their way of life.  I know this isn't what Deirdre said, but when I read her postings in this thread, I visualize her saying stuff like, &quot;Death to the intolerate hatemongers!&quot; hehehe.<br>
<br>
Regarding the idea of chaperones, hmmmm.  I could see that working for SOME teens, particularly the younger ones, but even if all you plan to do is hold hands, having someone looking over your shoulder all the time on a date would not be conducive to a relaxed mood.  Maybe if the chaperone kept their distance it would be okay.  I know if I had a daughter and Anarkhan went on a date with her, there would be very big, well-armed chaperones with bad attitudes who would be constantly cracking their knuckles and glaring at him and saying things like, &quot;Keep those hands where I can see them!&quot; hehehe<br>
<br>
Regarding having hordes of concubines and wives, you guys are too much! hehehehe!  Everyone that I have read about who went that route got all kinds of grief from it.  It just ain't worth it!  Oh, your adolescent fantasies tell you it would be worth it, but trust me, it isn't!  <br>
<br>
ACK!!! Just noticed the time.  I gotta get some more work done and then get to bed so I can get up for work in the morning.  Later, people!<br>
<br>
 <p>Argfeld<BR>
Level 58 Monk<BR>
Order of the Scattered Winds<BR>
Bertoxxulous<BR>
